# MALLOC VS CALLOC

- Malloc & calloc are both used to retain values even after the function is terminated (stack values are deleted, heap values remain).

When to Use malloc

Use malloc when speed is a priority, or when you plan to immediately overwrite the entire block of memory anyway, making initialization a waste of CPU cycles. 
You plan to fill the buffer immediately: E.g., fread or strcpy.
Performance is critical: You do not want to waste time zeroing out memory you will overwrite.
Small allocations: Where the cost of initialization is higher than the benefit.
Allocating a single item: Where you only need one struct or primitive type. 

When to Use calloc

Use calloc when you need a "clean slate" and want to avoid bugs related to reading uninitialized memory. 
Arrays and Structures: When allocating arrays of structs, especially if they contain pointers that should be initialized to NULL.
String Buffers: Ensuring the entire string buffer is zeroed (including the null terminator) prevents garbage data at the end of the string.
Safety/Security: calloc can protect against integer overflow vulnerabilities during multiplication (count * sizeof).
Defaulting to zero: When you want all variables initialized to 0, false, or NULL by default. 



